    "opinion": "As a delivery driver in Rome with four kids and not much time to waste, I see fake content on social media as just another problem to deal with practically. I spend about an hour daily checking Facebook and Instagram, mostly to see family photos and local news, but too often I come across posts that seem off—like exaggerated stories about politics or health tips that sound too good to be true. With my vocational diploma and a straightforward approach from my job, I don't overthink it; I just ignore most of it and focus on what matters. My parents had good education—my dad with a PhD and my mom finishing high school—so they taught me to question things, but honestly, I'm not very open to new ideas (my openness is low at 25), and I'm not that conscientious (score 3), so I don't go digging for facts. Instead, I rely on my moderate extraversion (score 41) to talk to friends or family if something seems fishy, and my low agreeableness (score 7) means I don't just believe everything I read. Being a native-born Italian and Muslim, I value truth in my faith and community, so I avoid sharing fake stuff that could cause trouble. My hobbies like hiking keep me grounded in real life, away from online drama. To manage fake content, I'd say: keep it simple. Don't trust every post, especially from strangers; check with people you know if it's important; and use that hour wisely—maybe skip social media and play a board game with the kids instead. It's about balancing time and not letting nonsense distract from what's real, like my deliveries or family time in Rome.",
